Nuclear fusion energy is produced by combining light atoms (deuturium or tritium - heavy isotopes of hydrogen) in a fusion reactor. Unfortunately, this form of energy is still in the research and development stage and is at least 50 years away from becoming a practical energy source. Its advantage lies in the vast amounts of hydrogen that lie in the Earth~’s oceans, which can supply anticipated global energy needs for centuries to come.

